= Practice

$
  "For" f(x) = sin(pi/x), lim_(x arrow 0) f(x) "does not exist."
$


= Sol
Consider two sequences $s_n$ and $t_n$ satisfy

$
  pi / s_n = - pi/2 - 2n pi, pi / t_n = pi / 2 + 2n pi, forall n in NN
$

i.e.

$
  s_n &= pi / (- pi/2 - 2n pi) = 2 / (- 1 - 4n), \
  t_n &= pi / (pi / 2 + 2n pi) = 2 / (1 + 4n).
$

We have $f(s_n) = -1$ and $f(t_n) = 1$ for all $n in NN$. Conclude that
$lim_(x arrow 0) f(x)$ does not exist.

